    <div class="elementListBrownSeparator"></div>



  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2324934384" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2324934384" />
    <a title="E.F.B." class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/39244832-e-f-b"><img alt="E.F.B." src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1424876183p2/39244832.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2324934384?book_show_action=true">Nov 19, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="E.F.B." class="user" itemprop="url" name="E.F.B." href="/user/show/39244832-e-f-b">E.F.B.</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/39244832-e-f-b?shelf=christian-fiction">christian-fiction</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/39244832-e-f-b?shelf=favorites">favorites</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/39244832-e-f-b?shelf=young-adult">young-adult</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/39244832-e-f-b?shelf=historical-fiction">historical-fiction</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/39244832-e-f-b?shelf=fairy-tale-retellings">fairy-tale-retellings</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/39244832-e-f-b?shelf=romance">romance</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2324934384" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer5646598422744273918">This was the first Aladdin retelling I&apos;ve ever read. It was written a little differently than Dickerson&apos;s previous books in this series because the hero and heroine knew each other from childhood this time (all the ones from previous books met for the first time in their mid to late teens) and because of this, she took the time to show us important moments from their friendship that spanned over years. It took a little getting used to, but once I did I think it worked well, and I do enjoy a good</span>
  <span id="freeText5646598422744273918" style="display:none">This was the first Aladdin retelling I've ever read. It was written a little differently than Dickerson's previous books in this series because the hero and heroine knew each other from childhood this time (all the ones from previous books met for the first time in their mid to late teens) and because of this, she took the time to show us important moments from their friendship that spanned over years. It took a little getting used to, but once I did I think it worked well, and I do enjoy a good childhood-friends-to-lovers romance. There's no chance of instalove and no doubt that the couple knows each other well enough to be in love. <br /><br />Speaking of the couple, Aladdin was a total sweetheart. So kind, respectful, and honorable toward Kirstyn and everyone, really. And yes, he didn't have much in the way of flaws aside from his own fears and insecurities, but sometimes, when it's a book isn't all that deep to begin with, I don't mind the love interest just being a genuinely good and nice person. <br /><br />And Kirstyn was sweet too. Appropriately innocent at the start, and as a middle child in such a large family, it made sense that she might feel overlooked and forgotten by them at times, but I liked that she learned otherwise. I also thought it was good that she was not <a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[kidnapped and held hostage for six month by a crazy and abusive man  <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span> with no emotional repercussions. Trauma is trauma and it only makes sense that she would feel lasting effects from that. But her family and Aladdin treated her with gentleness and understanding, as they should. <br /><br />As for the retelling itself, when I started this book, I didn't know if it would retell Disney's Aladdin or the original. I grew up with Disney's version since it came out the year I was born, but had never encountered the original. It bore absolutely no resemblance to Disney's version, so I pretty much didn't know what was going to happen. Right before I finished the book I did find a version of the original via Audible (which doesn't have a listing here on GR so I can't count it toward my reading goal, grrr) and listened to that... but this book didn't bear much resemblance to that, either. Admittedly, it's got to be hard to retell a story so steeped in magic and genies in a historical, non-magical setting, PLUS make the fairytale character interact with already established characters from your own world. And really, the original Aladdin isn't very long at all. On audio, it was only 15 minutes long. I did see where Dickerson drew her inspiration, though. She had Aladdin start out as a young boy forced to be a thief, and then his motivation as an adult was to make his fortune so he would feel able to provide for Kirstyn if and when they married. That motivation was in the original too, except the original Aladdin just wanted money to have money, so Dickerson's version actually had a better reason for it. XD<br /><br />As for critiques, Kirstyn had a couple of dense moments near the beginning. Let's just say that Duke Wilhelm needs to teach his kids never to go into a dark alley with anyone EVER. That was her first dense moment. The second was when she couldn't figure out who a certain woman was whose voice she could hear but whose face she couldn't see. It was obvious to me who it was from the moment the person <a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[ led her into the dark alley  <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span>. It just took her way too long to figure out that this particular individual was involved with her kidnapping. However, I did appreciate that Kirstyn never gave up hope and never stopped trying to get away.<br /><br />One complaint I see about this series is that the stories and characters aren't very deep, and I won't deny that. But if I wanted a deep read, I'd look to a different author. I read Dickerson's books because sometimes you just need something relaxing and fluffy that has a guaranteed happy ending, and The Orphan's Wish was no exception in that regard. Whether this retelling resembled the original or not, I still enjoyed it, which was a relief because for some reason I'd been afraid I wouldn't like it as much as Dickerson's previous books when I first got it. I don't even remember now why I thought that, though. I'm just glad I did end up enjoying it. <br /><br /><b>Content Advisory:</b><br /><br />Trigger warning: Abuse.<br /><br /><b>Violence:</b> <br /><br />As usual, Dickerson is great at writing loathsome villains, and this book's villain is no exception. He is crazy, manipulative, and abusive. While it never happens on the page he regularly beats his girlfriend for anything he considers annoying or a mistake, including beating her instead of Kirstyn (who they kidnapped) when Kirstyn tries to escape. <br /><br />Again, the actual blows aren't shown in any way, but once, when he drags Kirstyn back by her hair after an attempted escape, Kirstyn sees that his girlfriend has a black eye, swollen lip, and generally appears in pain. When Kirstyn tries to convince the girlfriend that she shouldn't put up with this, the villain hits Kirstyn, too, and because the scene is from her perspective, pain is described as she falls backward and her head hits the ground. Her lip also bleeds. She then witnesses the villain make nice with his girlfriend, kissing and nuzzling her and trying to act like what he just did was logical. <br /><br />While this^ is only shown once, we learn from Kirstyn's thoughts that the cycle of the villain beating his girlfriend and then convincing her to stay with him by kissing and saying he loves her happens frequently. Kirstyn herself learns how to avoid the worst of his abuse, but is forced to be tied up with ropes around her wrists the vast majority of the time and ends up with bleeding wounds and scars from them. (Wrist wounds described.) <br /><br />After Kirstyn is returned to her family, she experiences PTSD symptoms. She has nightmares, loud noises scare her so badly she screams and shakes, and a younger brother grabbing her wrist frightens her so badly she screams and shakes. She fears her family thinks she's lost her mind, but as stated in my review, they and Aladdin treat her with much love and gentleness, and her father observes that she's experiencing something like his knights experience after battle. <br /><br />The villain makes threats related to cutting Aladdin's throat in his sleep, and even attacks him with a battle ax, but ends up defeated and killed with a sword to the heart. (No blood described.)<br /><br /><b>Sexual/Romantic:</b> <br /><br />Aladdin and Kirstyn fall in love slowly over the course of a years-long friendship. For the majority of the book this is expressed with them thinking fondly of each other, thinking how they love the other person, but aren't sure the other person loves them in that way. They sometimes think they want to kiss the other person, but this is not constant. When they finally establish that their love is reciprocated they kiss about three or four times. Some of these kisses are passionate and described in a few lines, but not overly detailed or lengthy. They kiss on the cheek a couple times, too.<br /><br /><b> Spiritual:</b> <br /><br />The spiritual content in this one felt a little light. It mostly was Kirstyn trusting God would help her and bring her kidnapper to justice, and Aladdin also trusting God and occasionally getting little signs that seemed to be from God. (Like a stork, a bird special to him and Kirstyn, flying overhead, reminding him to pray for her, or a stork nest being on the roof of a house he was going to buy for her.)</span>
  <a data-text-id="5646598422744273918" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


